lee, Teviotdale, Scotland":"Crosslee, Renfrewshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1162–1214":"1162–1214","1165–Female":"1165–Deceased","1185–1231":"1185–1231","1115–1168":"1115–1168","1140–1189":"1140–1189","1214":"1214","1115":"1115","1168":"1168","1189":"1189","1231":"1231","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1162":"1162","1184":"1184","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Rankilburn, Crosslee, Teviotdale, Scotland":"Crosslee, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Scott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (Down): habitational and ethnic name from Middle English <i>Scot</i> ‘man from Scotland’. There is no evidence that the surname denoted either of the earlier senses of <i>Scot</i> as ‘(Gaelic-speaking) Irishman’ or ‘man from Alba’, the Gaelic-speaking region of Scotland north of the river Forth. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","English and Scottish: from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Scot</i> (Old English <i>Scott</i>, possibly also Old Norse <i>Skotr</i>), only certainly attested in northern England.","English: variant of   Scutt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Scutt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Pierre.","Americanized form of Dutch   Schutte   ‘archer’.","English: nickname for a short person, from Middle English <i>scut(e)</i> ‘short’, or else for a swift runner, from Middle English <i>scut</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"Michael","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of a common biblical name (meaning ‘who is like God?’ in Hebrew) borne by one of the archangels, the protector of the ancient Hebrews, who is also regarded as a saint of the Catholic Church. In the Middle Ages, Michael was regarded as captain of the heavenly host (see Revelation 12:7–9), symbol of the Church Militant, and patron of soldiers. He was often depicted bearing a flaming sword. The name is also borne by a Persian prince and ally of Belshazzar mentioned in the Book of Daniel. Since the early 1900s it has been one of the most enduringly popular boys' names in the English-speaking world.  See also  Michal ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Michael Scott of Rankilburn was born in 1162, in Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland, his father, Richard Scott of Rankilburn, was 47 and his mother, Alicia De Mola, was 22. He married Margaret Syras in 1184, in Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1214, in his hometown, at the age of 52, and was buried in Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland."},"et":{"1162–1214":"1162–1214","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1185–1231":"1185–1231","1115–1168":"1115–1168","1140–1189":"1140–1189","1214":"1214","1115":"1115","1168":"1168","1189":"1189","1231":"1231","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1162":"1162","1184":"1184","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Rankilburn, Crosslee, Teviotdale, Scotland":"Crosslee, Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1162–1214":"1162–1214","1165–Female":"1165–Kuollut","1185–1231":"1185–1231","1115–1168":"1115–1168","1140–1189":"1140–1189","1214":"1214","1115":"1115","1168":"1168","1189":"1189","1231":"1231","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1162":"1162","1184":"1184","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Rankilburn, Crosslee, Teviotdale, Scotland":"Crosslee, Renfrewshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1162–1214":"1162–1214","1165–Female":"1165–Décédée","1185–1231":"1185–1231","1115–1168":"1115–1168","1140–1189":"1140–1189","1214":"1214","1115":"1115","1168":"1168","1189":"1189","1231":"1231","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1162":"1162","1184":"1184","1140":"1140","1160